-- Japanese Stocks Advance on Earnings, Commodities; Topix Erases 2010 Loss
-- B y   A k i k o   I k e d a
-- 2010-12-29T07:08:03Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-12-29/japan-s-nikkei-225-drops-for-second-day-on-yen-s-advance-advantest-falls.html
Japan’s  stocks  climbed, erasing the
Topix index’s year-to-date loss, as the outlook for corporate
earnings improved and after oil and metal prices rose yesterday.  Citizen Holdings Co., a watchmaker, gained 1.1 percent
after the Nikkei newspaper said the company’s earnings increased.
Aeon Credit Service Co., a credit-card company, jumped 4.6
percent after turning to a nine-month profit. Mitsui & Co.,
which counts commodities as its largest source of profit,
climbed 0.7 percent.  Hitachi Ltd. , a maker of products ranging
from washing machines to nuclear reactors, advanced 2.4 percent
after the Sankei newspaper said the company will win orders for
rail cars in Britain.  The Nikkei 225 Stock Average gained 0.5 percent to
10,344.54 at the close in Tokyo. The broader  Topix  index rose
0.6 percent to 908.01, the highest level since May 19. About six
times as many stocks advanced as declined. All 33 industry
groups in the Topix increased.  As corporate earnings recover, “fear that stocks will
decline seems to be easing,” said  Naoteru Teraoka , general
manager at Tokyo-based Chuo Mitsui Asset Management Co., which
oversees about $26 billion. “Japanese stocks will likely
continue rising to catch up with other markets.”  The Topix has risen less than 0.1 percent in 2010, compared
with gains of 13 percent by the Standard & Poor’s 500 Index and
10 percent by the Stoxx Europe 600 Index. Stocks in the Japanese
benchmark are valued at 15.8 times estimated earnings on average,
compared with 14.8 times for the S&P 500 and 12.4 times for the
Stoxx 600.  Corporate Earnings  Citizen increased 1.1 percent to 568 yen. The company’s
operating  profit  for the April-December period almost doubled to
about 14 billion yen ($169 million), boosted by strong sales of
watches, the Nikkei newspaper reported without saying where it
obtained the information.  Aeon Credit Service leapt 4.6 percent to 1,148 yen, the
highest close since April 6. The company turned to a nine-month
net income of 5.99 billion yen from a loss of 4.02 billion yen a
year earlier. The  index group  that includes Aeon Credit rose the
most among the 33 industry groups in the Topix.  Shimamura Co., an apparel retailer, increased 1.6 percent
to 7,640 yen. The company said nine-month net income advanced
9.4 percent to 18 billion yen, with a 2.1 percent rise in sales.  Oil, Metals  “Money flows into risk assets, including commodities, has
continued, so gains in commodities should support the market,”
said  Hiroichi Nishi , an equities manager in Tokyo at Nikko
Cordial Securities Inc.  Mitsui & Co. climbed 0.7 percent to 1,343 yen. Japan
Petroleum Exploration Co., the nation’s second-biggest oil
driller, gained 2 percent to 3,135 yen. Sumitomo Metal Mining
Co., a copper and gold producer, gained 0.8 percent to 1,434 yen.  Crude oil for February delivery climbed 0.5 percent to
$91.46 a barrel in New York yesterday. Copper futures increased
1.1 percent in New York to a record for a second straight day.
Gold futures gained 1.6 percent in New York yesterday, the
biggest advance for a most-active contract since Nov. 4.  Sojitz Corp. , a trading company, climbed 3.5 percent to 177
yen after China cut its export quotas for rare-earths by 35
percent in the first round of permits for 2011. The company has
signed a deal with Australia’s Lynas Corp. to support Australian
rare-earth developers’ plans to double capacity.  Hitachi Advances  Hitachi  rose 2.4 percent to 425 yen, a level not seen since
December 2008. The company will win an order for 1,400 rail cars
for four routes in Britain, the Sankei newspaper said. Also, the
company is reviewing cost structures in a quarter of its 40
business areas, the Nikkei newspaper reported, citing an
interview with President Hiroaki Nakanishi.  U.S. retail sales, excluding autos, rose 5.5 percent to
$584 billion from Nov. 5 through Dec. 24 for the biggest
holiday-season increase since 2005, according to MasterCard
Advisors’ SpendingPulse, which measures sales by all payment
forms.  “Investors will further price in the strong year-end sales
as many people have just come back from holidays,” Chuo Mitsui
Asset Management’s Teraoka said.  To contact the reporter on this story:
 Akiko Ikeda  in Tokyo at 
